
## ðŸ”¹ What Is a Read-Only Property?

A **read-only property** is a property that allows you to **get/read** the value, but **not set/change** it directly.

Itâ€™s like having:

```cpp
cout << obj.Name;  // âœ… allowed
obj.Name = "Ali";  // âŒ not allowed
```

---

## ðŸ”¸ How to Do It in C++ with `__declspec(property)`

You only define the `get` accessor â€” **no `put`**.

### âœ… Example:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {
private:
    int _id;

public:
    // Constructor
    Student(int id) {
        _id = id;
    }

    // Getter only
    int GetID() {
        return _id;
    }

    // Read-only property (no 'put')
    __declspec(property(get = GetID)) int ID;
};

int main() {
    Student s(123);

    cout << "Student ID: " << s.ID << endl;  // âœ… allowed

    // s.ID = 456;   // âŒ error: no 'put' function defined

    return 0;
}
```

---

## ðŸ” Summary

| Feature            | Included? |
| ------------------ | --------- |
| `get = GetID`      | âœ… Yes     |
| `put = SetID`      | âŒ No      |
| Can read `obj.ID`  | âœ… Yes     |
| Can write `obj.ID` | âŒ No      |

---

## ðŸ’¡ If You're Not Using MSVC

If you're not using Microsoft Visual C++, this won't work, because `__declspec(property)` is not standard C++. In that case, you'd just use `GetID()` directly as a method.
